# {{ _wt_slug }}

{{ wt.description | default('A shared work directory.') }}

Doing things by hand in the shared **work directory**. Claude users don't need
this — `EnterWorktree` (via `.claude/hooks/worktree-create`) sets a worktree up
for you. This is the human guide.

The bare git repository lives at `{{ _wt_repo }}`; this directory's `.git` file
points at it, so you can run git here to **look things up**, but you cannot edit
anything from here (the pad reports as a bare repo, so there is no working tree).

## Looking things up

Run git directly in this directory against the live repo:

```bash
git log --oneline -20 main              # recent history
git branch                              # what work is in flight
git show main:path/to/file              # read a file at a ref
git log --oneline work/<category>/<branch>   # someone's in-progress branch
```

## Create a worktree

Each piece of work gets its own worktree at
`{{ _wt_workdir }}/<category>/<branch>` on a branch `work/<category>/<branch>`.
New worktrees always branch from `main`:

```bash
git -C {{ _wt_repo }} worktree add {{ _wt_workdir }}/feature/my-thing -b work/feature/my-thing main
cd {{ _wt_workdir }}/feature/my-thing
```

To build on another branch that isn't merged yet, base it there instead of
`main`:

```bash
git -C {{ _wt_repo }} worktree add {{ _wt_workdir }}/feature/my-thing -b work/feature/my-thing work/feature/other-thing
```

…or start from `main` and merge that branch in once you're inside:

```bash
git merge work/feature/other-thing
```

The name is `<category>/<branch>`: `<category>` groups related work (created on
demand); `<branch>` is a URL slug (lowercase `a-z`/`0-9`, starts with a letter,
at least one `-`, at most 40 characters).

## Who merges what

Open an MR against `main`; the maintainer reviews and merges. Don't push to
`main` from a `work/…` branch — the bare repo's hooks reject it.

See [Shared Worktrees 🌳](https://cute-devops.patterns.how/patterns/approaches/shared-worktrees) for the full pattern.

